{{For|the political figure|C. B. Collins (treasurer)}} '''Christopher Barry Collins''' is a [[cosmology|cosmologist]] who has written many papers with [[Stephen Hawking]]. He is a [[professor emeritus]] of [[applied mathematics]] at the [[University of Waterloo]].<ref>[https://uwaterloo.ca/applied-mathematics/about/people/cbcollin Faculty profile], Univ. of Waterloo, retrieved 2015-07-22.</ref>
Collins earned his Ph.D. in 1972 from the [[University of Cambridge]] under the supervision of F. Gerard Friedlander.<ref>{{mathgenealogy|id=127502|name=Christopher Barry Collins}}</ref> Among his works with Hawking is a 1973 paper that uses the [[anthropic principle]] to provide a solution to the [[flatness problem]].<ref>{{citation|title=Space and Time in the Modern Universe|first=P. C. W.|last=Davies|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1977|isbn=9780521291514|page=215|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SZI5AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA215}}.</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Cosmic Enigmas|volume=10|series=Masters of Modern Physics|first=Joseph|last=Silk|publisher=Springer|year=1994|isbn=9781563960611|page=35|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ovXYxdSuOhkC&pg=PA35}}.</ref><ref>{{citation|title=The Anthropic Principle: Man as the Focal Point of Nature|first=Reinhard|last=Breuer|publisher=Springer|year=2013|isbn=9781489967411|page=111|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZXkECAAAQBAJ&pg=PA111}}.</ref>
